      <entry corresp="til" type="particle">
        <form xml:lang="ta">til</form>
        <gramGrp>
            <gram>enclitic particle</gram>
        </gramGrp>
        <sense>
            <usg xml:lang="en">a particle used with the optative</usg>
            <cit source="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Purananuru/PN284.xml?id=PN284&amp;w=0,4">
                <q xml:lang="ta"><w>varuka-til</w> <w>val-<c type="geminated">l</c>ē</w> <w>varuka-til</w> <w>val</w> <w><c type="geminated">l</c>eṉa</w></q>
                <q xml:lang="en">saying, <q>please come quickly, please come quickly!</q></q>
                <ref target="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Purananuru/PN284.xml?highlight=%5Bid%3DPN284%5D%20.l%3Anth-of-type(1)"><title xml:lang="ta">Puṟanāṉūṟu</title> 284, line 1</ref>
            </cit>
            <cit source="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Kuruntokai/KT14.xml?id=KT14&amp;w=13,14">
                <q xml:lang="ta"><w>peṟuka-tillamma</w> <w>yāṉ-ē</w></q>
                <q xml:lang="en">If only I could get her!</q>
                <ref target="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Kuruntokai/KT14.xml?highlight=%5Bid%3DKT14%5D%20.l%3Anth-of-type(3)"><title xml:lang="ta">Kuṟuntokai</title> 14, line 3</ref>
            </cit>
            <note xml:lang="en">
This particle is almost always enclitic with the optative in <foreign xml:lang="ta">-ka</foreign>. It may also be expanded to <foreign xml:lang="ta">tilla</foreign> or <foreign xml:lang="ta">tillamma</foreign>. The <title xml:lang="ta">Tolkāppiyam</title> states three functions that are conveyed by this particle — indicating a wish, time (i.e., the contrast between the present and a desired future action), or a subtext. It further specifies that the indication of a wish is only relevant with a verb in the first person. For a full discussion, see <title xml:lang="ta">Collatikāram</title> <ref target="../Tolkappiyam/TolC253.xml">253</ref> &amp; <ref target="../Tolkappiyam/TolC260.xml">260</ref>.
            </note>
        </sense>
        <sense>
            <usg xml:lang="en">an interjection</usg>
            <cit source="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Ainkurunuru/Aink319.xml?id=Aink319&amp;w=15,18">
                <q xml:lang="ta"><w>maṟantaṉar-ō</w> <w>til</w> <w>maṟavā</w> <w>nam-<c type="geminated">m</c>ē</w></q>
                <q xml:lang="en">Alas, has he forgotten us, who haven't forgotten him?</q>
                <ref target="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Ainkurunuru/Aink319.xml?highlight=%5Bid%3DAink319%5D%20.l%3Anth-of-type(4)"><title xml:lang="ta">Aiṅkuṟunūṟu</title> 319, line 4</ref>
            </cit>
            <note xml:lang="en">
An extraordinary usage of <foreign xml:lang="ta">til</foreign> occurs in the <title xml:lang="ta">Aiṅkuṟunūṟu</title>, where it seems to be an interjection following the particle <foreign xml:lang="ta">ō</foreign> (241 &amp; 319) or following a first-person verb or pronominalised noun (<ref target="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Ainkurunuru/Aink204.xml">204</ref>). Examples of this kind are not recorded elsewhere in the corpus, nor are they cited by the <title xml:lang="ta">Tolkāppiyam</title> commentators. 
            </note>
        </sense>
